      "beat_count": 6,
      "conditioning_notes": "`<CHAR_A>`'s love of calling it straight and fear of being managed surfaces in the refusal to be warmed up, carb-loaded, or softened — and in the flat \"they boo, that's their job.\" The crack of genuine recognition in narreme_005 (\"you're better at the opening\") lands harder because it costs `<CHAR_A>` something to say it without a buffer of irony. `<CHAR_B>`'s love of believing in people drives the earnest worry about the crowd — not stage fright exactly, but a need for the thing to land with people, to matter to them — and the fear of being naive shows up in how quickly they scan `<CHAR_A>` for confirmation that their optimism isn't misplaced. `<CHAR_C>`'s love of taking care and fear of not being needed runs the whole background register: the snack pressed into hands, the \"I'll be right here,\" the waiting. The Arena location is never named but governs everything — characters perform, the crowd is a presence even when silent, the exit is always on the other side of an audience. The stakes aren't life-or-death; they're the watched-moment stakes that a public arena makes enormous."
